"Salm J.-O., Kimmel K., Uri V., Mander Ü.","Global warming potential of drained and undrained Peatlands in Estonia: A synthesis",2009,"Wetlands","29","4",,"1081","1092",,,10.1672/08-206.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-72449127067&partnerID=40&md5=2bf524731eb95474e2abdffaa4fc4e5d","Department of Geography, Institute of Ecology and Earth Sciences, University of Tartu, 46 Vanemuise St., Tartu 51014, Estonia; Estonian Fund for Nature, 3 Magasini St., Tartu 51005, Estonia; Institute of Forestry and Rural Engineering, Estonian University of Life Sciences, 5 Kreutzwaldi St., Tartu 51014, Estonia","Salm, J.-O., Department of Geography, Institute of Ecology and Earth Sciences, University of Tartu, 46 Vanemuise St., Tartu 51014, Estonia, Estonian Fund for Nature, 3 Magasini St., Tartu 51005, Estonia; Kimmel, K., Department of Geography, Institute of Ecology and Earth Sciences, University of Tartu, 46 Vanemuise St., Tartu 51014, Estonia; Uri, V., Institute of Forestry and Rural Engineering, Estonian University of Life Sciences, 5 Kreutzwaldi St., Tartu 51014, Estonia; Mander, Ü., Department of Geography, Institute of Ecology and Earth Sciences, University of Tartu, 46 Vanemuise St., Tartu 51014, Estonia","We estimated the global warming potential of Estonian peatlands (transitional fens and ombrotrophic bogs) based on greenhouse gases (GHG) CO2, CH4, and N2O and carbon (C) accrual in biomass, and the effects of drainage on these processes. Data were derived from a review of the literature of boreal peatlands. Areal estimates of peatland types were multiplied with the values of the interquartile range of literature-derived GHG fluxes. The effect of drainage and radiative forcing of Estonian peatlands were also evaluated. Annual emission of CO2, CH4, and N2O is estimated to be 278 to 1,056 × 10 3 of CO2 equivalent (eq), of which CO2 makes up 22 to 44, CH4 53 to 73, and N2O 3 to 5. The annual efflux is 419 to 676 × 103 CO2 eq year-1 from drained peatlands, and -141 to 380 × 10 3 CO2 eq year-1 from the undrained peatlands. The annual loss of C from peatlands is estimated to be 38 to 86 tons C × 10 3 year-1. Thus due to drainage, Estonia's transitional fens and ombrotrophic bogs have gone from being sinks to sources of C. © 2009 The Society of Wetland Scientists.","Carbon dioxide; Climate change; Methane; Nitrous oxide","carbon dioxide; carbon sink; drainage; emission inventory; global warming; greenhouse gas; nitrous oxide; peatland; radiative forcing; Estonia",,,,,,"Alm, J., Shurpali, N.J., Minkkinen, K., Aro, L., Hytonen, J., Laurila, T., Lohila, A., Laine, J., Emission factors and their uncertainty for the exchange of CO2, CH4 and N2O in Finnish managed peatlands (2007) Boreal Environment Research, 12, pp. 191-209; Arold, I., (2005) Estonian Landscapes, , Tartu University, Tartu, Estonia (In Estonian); Aurela, M., Laurila, T., Tuovinen, J.-P., The timing of snow melt controls the annual CO2 balance in a subarctic fen (2004) Geophysical Research Letters, 31 (16), pp. L161191-4. , DOI 10.1029/2004GL020315; Bos, R.M., Huissteden, K., Plassche, O., Amodel-based of CO2 andCH4 fluxes in coastal peatlands (western Netherlands) for different climate andmanagement scenarios (2003) Human Influences on Carbon Fluxes in Coastal Peatlands; Process Analysis, Quantification and Prediction, , R. M. van den Bos (ed.). Ph.D. Dissertation. Vrije Universiteit, Amsterdam, Netherlands; Bridgham, S.D., Megonigal, J.P., Keller, J.K., Bliss, N.B., Trettin, C., The carbon storage of North American wetlands (2006) Wetlands, 26, pp. 889-916; Broadmeadow, M., Matthews, R., Forests, carbon and climate change: The UK contribution (2003) Forestry Commission, , Edinburgh, UK. FCIN048/FG(ECD)/BTH-2.5K/JUN03; Cleary, J., Roulet, N.T., Moore, T.R., Greenhouse gas emissions from canadian peat extraction, 1990-2000: A lifecycle analysis (2005) Ambio, 34, pp. 456-461; Crill, P., Hargreaves, K., Korhola, A., The role of peat in finnish greenhouse gas balan